Manages a Wordpress project Rails-ishly.

* <tt>wordpressify</tt> sets up a new project and upgrades an existing one to the latest Wordpress.
* <tt>cap deploy:setup</tt> and <tt>cap deploy</tt> do the right thing, handling <tt>wp-config.php</tt>.
* <tt>cap deploy:upgrade</tt> additionally backs up your database and disables your plugins, {as recommended}[http://codex.wordpress.org/Upgrading_WordPress_Extended].
* <tt>script/server</tt> fires up lighttpd for local development.


==Getting Started

 $ sudo gem install wordpress --source http://gems.matthewtodd.org
 $ wordpressify blog
 $ cd blog
 $ ls *
 Capfile

 config:
 boot.rb              lighttpd-mimetypes.conf wp-config-sample.php
 deploy.rb            lighttpd.conf           wp-config.php

 public:
 index.php            wp-config.php@          wp-rdf.php
 license.txt          wp-content/             wp-register.php
 readme.html          wp-cron.php             wp-rss.php
 wp-admin/            wp-feed.php             wp-rss2.php
 wp-app.php           wp-includes/            wp-settings.php
 wp-atom.php          wp-links-opml.php       wp-trackback.php
 wp-blog-header.php   wp-login.php            xmlrpc.php
 wp-comments-post.php wp-mail.php
 wp-commentsrss2.php  wp-pass.php

 script:
 server*
 $

==script/server

 $ sudo port install lighttpd mysql5 +server php5 +fastcgi +mysql5
 $ sudo launchctl load -w /Library/LaunchDaemons/org.macports.mysql5.plist
 $ mysqladmin -u root create blog
 $ script/server

==Wordpress Releases

This gem depends on <tt>wordpress-release</tt> for its copy of the Wordpress code.

See http://docs.matthewtodd.org/wordpress-release for more -- the gem version number matches the bundled version of Wordpress.